#### M-10: Evaluating a Big Purchase
*Strategy:* Research + Decide
*See also:* Tr-1: Buying a Car (the single most common big purchase), Ch-1: Shopping Your Values (for evaluating who you're buying from), Ho-3: Right to Repair (for durability and long-term cost)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One has observed that the phrase "0% APR for 36 months" appears in advertising with a frequency that suggests, to the casual observer, that financing large purchases at no cost has become a simple act of generosity on the part of retailers. It has not. The 0% offer is a customer acquisition tool: the retailer has calculated that a meaningful percentage of purchasers will miss a payment, triggering deferred interest — in some cases retroactively applied to the entire original balance at rates exceeding 25%. The furniture, the appliance, the automobile — whatever the object, the financing is not a courtesy extended to the buyer. It is a bet placed against them. One's Agent is rather useful for reading the terms of that bet before one accepts it._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I'm considering a major purchase and I want to make sure
I'm thinking about it clearly.
The purchase:
--- What: [car / appliance / furniture / electronics / home
   renovation / other]
--- Price: [sticker price or range]
--- Financing offered: [0% APR / store credit card / loan /
   paying cash / not sure yet]
--- Timeline: [need it now / can wait / replacing something broken]
--- New vs. used: [considering both / committed to one / not sure]
Please help me:
1. Calculate the total cost of ownership — not just the price tag,
   but maintenance, insurance, depreciation, energy costs,
   and anything else I'll pay over the life of this thing
2. Decode the financing: if there's a 0% APR offer, what are
   the actual terms? What happens if I miss a payment?
   What's the deferred interest clause?
3. Help me compare: new vs. used vs. refurbished — what's the
   real cost difference when I factor in lifespan and repair?
4. Am I buying at the right time? Are there seasonal patterns
   or model-year transitions that affect price?
5. What's the "walk away" number — at what price does this
   stop making financial sense for someone in my situation?
:::
*What to do with the Output:* The sticker price is not the price. For a car, the total cost of ownership includes insurance, fuel, maintenance, registration, depreciation, and financing. A $30,000 car at 7% APR over 72 months costs $36,500 in payments. If it depreciates to $12,000 in six years, the total cost of having the car was $24,500 plus insurance and gas. Your Agent can run this math for any purchase. The question is not "can I afford the payment?" --- that is the question the salesperson wants you to ask. The question is "what does this actually cost me over the time I'll own it?"

::: science
Deferred interest financing --- the "0% APR" model used by most furniture stores, electronics retailers, and medical providers --- applies the full accumulated interest retroactively if the balance is not paid in full by the promotional period's end. Consumer Financial Protection Bureau research found that approximately 43% of deferred interest plans result in the consumer paying interest, with the average retroactive interest charge exceeding the amount the consumer would have paid under a standard interest plan from the start.[^m10-1]
:::


::: tip
_"I'm looking at [item] for [$X] with '0% APR for 24 months.' Explain the deferred interest terms and calculate exactly what I'll owe if I pay it off on time vs. if I miss the deadline by one month."_
:::


::: meme
The 72-month auto loan was once considered predatory. It is now the most common car loan term in America. The 84-month loan — seven years — is the fastest-growing segment. The purpose of extending the loan term is not to make the car more affordable. It is to make the _payment_ smaller so the buyer will accept a higher purchase price. The car does not know how long you are paying for it, but the bank does, and it is delighted. [_The Simpsons_:S3E11 "Burns Verkaufen der Kraftwerk"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burns_Verkaufen_der_Kraftwerk), 1991, understood the buy-vs-hold math better than most personal finance books: Homer gets $5,200 for his stock and immediately spends it, because the money felt like a windfall rather than a position.
:::


::: fairness
Dealer markup, financing terms, and trade-in offers vary based on the buyer's perceived negotiating power — and studies consistently show that Black and Hispanic buyers are offered higher financing rates and pay more for identical vehicles. If your Agent helps you calculate a fair price, bring that number to the dealership. Information asymmetry is leverage. Having the number in writing — from a source the dealer cannot see — is how you close the gap. See Tr-1 for the full car-buying entry.
:::


::: also
For major electronics and appliances, checking current prices, reliability data, and seasonal sales patterns requires web search, which is free in Gemini, ChatGPT, and Copilot. In Claude, web search requires the paid tier. See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Consumer Reports reliability data vs. marketing claims. CR's annual reliability survey covers automobiles, appliances, and electronics. The data frequently contradicts brand perception — the most advertised brands are not the most reliable. The entry should point the reader toward CR (subscription required) and note that your Agent can summarize publicly available reliability data and recall notices. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: The "buy used" calculus for cars. A new car loses approximately 20% of its value in the first year and 60% over five years. A three-year-old certified pre-owned vehicle captures most of the depreciation curve while still carrying a warranty. The exception: when interest rates on new cars are significantly lower than used car rates (manufacturer incentives), the financing math can favor new. The entry should help the reader compare total cost, not monthly payment. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Big purchases carry emotional weight that financial analysis does not capture. The new couch is not just a couch — it is the feeling of having made it, of deserving something nice, of the apartment finally looking like an adult lives there. The salesperson knows this. The financing exists because the emotional urgency of "I want this now" reliably overrides the rational calculation of "this will cost me 28% more if I finance it." The entry should not shame the desire. It should give the reader the numbers so the desire and the math can negotiate honestly. -->

[^m10-1]: CFPB. (2023). ["The Consumer Credit Card Market."](https://www.consumerfinance.gov/data-research/research-reports/the-consumer-credit-card-market/) Deferred interest findings from CFPB supervisory examinations and enforcement actions.
